The Strangers In Familiarity:

The 7:47 express hums through industrial outskirts. Two strangers, both staring at the same raindrop racing down the window.
Stranger A: "Funny how rain smells different here. Not like... back there."
Stranger B: without looking "The quad always smelled like wet stone and cafeteria fries."
A: turns sharply "Wait—quad with the cracked bell tower? Where the ivy grew backwards because of the wind tunnel?"
B: finally meeting eyes "And the vending machine that only ever had one lemon-lime soda left? Always warm?"
A: leaning forward "The library basement that flooded every March..."
B: "...but the piano in the practice room stayed perfectly in tune." pause "Which is impossible, because—"
A & B together: "—the humidity should've warped the soundboard."
Silence. The train enters a tunnel. In the darkness, their reflections merge.
A: "I can't picture the name. Just... green uniforms? No, that wasn't it."
B: "There was a ghost story. About the girl who left her textbook—"
A: "—in the clock tower. And every hour, you'd hear pages turning that weren't there." quietly "I never told anyone I heard them too."
B: pulls out a worn keychain—blank, no engraving "I still have this. Found it in my bag graduation day. Never knew what it opened."
A: reaches into pocket, produces identical keychain "Me too."
The train emerges from the tunnel. They're approaching the city now.
B: "Maybe we didn't go to school together. Maybe we just... both dreamed the same place."
A: watching the rain start to fall upward against the train's speed "Then why do I remember your handwriting on the whiteboard? The way you'd draw your sevens with the line through them?"
B: smiling sadly "And I remember you always sat in the left corner of the lecture hall. Even when it was empty. Like you were saving a seat for someone who never came."
The conductor announces the next stop. Neither moves.
A: "What if we get off at the next station? Just... keep sitting here. See if the school finds us instead."
B: quietly "What if it already did?"
The train slows. The rain stops. In the sudden silence, they can almost hear pages turning somewhere far above them.

